{
  "A refracting telescope uses _____ to gather and focus light.": "",
  "Mirrors": "",
  "Prisms": "",
  "Antennas": "",
  "Lenses": "",
  "Refracting telescopes use glass lenses to bend (refract) light to a focal point. They were the first type of telescope used in astronomy.": "",
  "A reflecting telescope uses _____ to gather light.": "",
  "Filters": "",
  "Crystals": "",
  "Reflecting telescopes use curved mirrors (typically parabolic) to gather and focus light. Newton invented the first practical reflecting telescope.": "",
  "Which telescope was launched into space and orbits above Earth's atmosphere?": "",
  "Arecibo Telescope": "",
  "Keck Telescope": "",
  "Very Large Telescope": "",
  "Hubble Space Telescope": "",
  "The Hubble Space Telescope orbits above Earth's atmosphere, giving it sharp images free from atmospheric distortion. It was launched in 1990.": "",
  "Radio telescopes detect which type of electromagnetic radiation?": "",
  "Radio waves": "",
  "X-rays": "",
  "Visible light": "",
  "Gamma rays": "",
  "Radio telescopes use large dish antennas to detect radio waves from space. They can operate day or night and through clouds, unlike optical telescopes.": "",
  "What is one advantage of space-based telescopes over ground-based ones?": "",
  "They avoid distortion from Earth's atmosphere": "",
  "They are closer to the stars": "",
  "They are cheaper to build": "",
  "They are easier to repair": "",
  "Earth's atmosphere blurs and absorbs certain wavelengths of light. Space telescopes like Hubble and JWST avoid this problem entirely, producing much sharper images.": "",
  "The James Webb Space Telescope (JWST) primarily observes in which part of the electromagnetic spectrum?": "",
  "Gamma ray": "",
  "Ultraviolet": "",
  "Infrared": "",
  "Radio": "",
  "JWST is optimized for infrared observations, allowing it to see through dust clouds and observe the earliest galaxies formed after the Big Bang.": "",
  "Which space probe has traveled beyond our solar system into interstellar space?": "",
  "International Space Station": "",
  "Mars Rover Curiosity": "",
  "Voyager 1": "",
  "Voyager 1, launched in 1977, became the first human-made object to enter interstellar space in 2012, after passing beyond the heliosphere.": "",
  "A common problem with large refracting telescopes is:": "",
  "Chromatic aberration — different colors focus at different points": "",
  "They cannot be pointed at the sky": "",
  "They can only see in infrared light": "",
  "They require nuclear power": "",
  "Chromatic aberration occurs because glass lenses bend different wavelengths of light by different amounts, causing color fringing. This limits the practical size of refracting telescopes.": "",
  "The Chandra space telescope is designed to detect:": "",
  "Sound waves": "",
  "The Chandra X-ray Observatory detects X-ray emissions from hot, energetic regions of the universe such as exploded stars, galaxy clusters, and matter around black holes.": "",
  "What does a larger telescope aperture (opening) allow?": "",
  "It blocks more starlight": "",
  "It collects more light, showing fainter objects": "",
  "It makes the telescope lighter": "",
  "It reduces the field of view": "",
  "A larger aperture gathers more photons, allowing the telescope to detect fainter objects and resolve finer details. This is why modern telescopes have mirrors many meters across.": "",
  "What is 'aperture' in the context of a telescope?": "",
  "The type of camera attached to the telescope": "",
  "The brightness of the object being observed": "",
  "The diameter of the main lens or mirror that gathers light": "",
  "The length of the telescope tube": "",
  "Aperture is the diameter of a telescope's primary light-gathering element (lens or mirror). A larger aperture means more light-gathering power and better resolution.": "",
  "What is 'chromatic aberration'?": "",
  "The redshift of distant galaxies": "",
  "A defect where a lens focuses different colors of light at different points": "",
  "The twinkling of stars caused by the atmosphere": "",
  "A type of mirror used in reflecting telescopes": "",
  "Chromatic aberration occurs because glass refracts (bends) different wavelengths by different amounts. Blue light bends more than red, creating color fringes. Reflecting telescopes avoid this problem because mirrors reflect all colors equally.": "",
  "What is the 'electromagnetic spectrum'?": "",
  "The sound waves produced by stars": "",
  "The visible colors of a rainbow only": "",
  "The gravitational waves from black holes": "",
  "The full range of electromagnetic radiation, from radio waves to gamma rays": "",
  "The electromagnetic spectrum spans all types of electromagnetic radiation: radio, microwave, infrared, visible, ultraviolet, X-ray, and gamma ray. Different telescopes observe different parts of this spectrum.": "",
  "What is a 'radio telescope'?": "",
  "A handheld device for listening to space sounds": "",
  "A telescope that can only see planets": "",
  "A telescope that plays radio music while observing": "",
  "A telescope that detects radio-wavelength radiation from space using a dish antenna": "",
  "Radio telescopes use large dish antennas to collect radio waves emitted by celestial objects. The Arecibo dish (305 m) and FAST (500 m) are famous examples.": "",
  "What is 'light-gathering power'?": "",
  "A telescope's ability to collect photons, determined by its aperture size": "",
  "The weight of the telescope's mirrors": "",
  "The amount of electricity a telescope requires": "",
  "The speed at which a telescope can rotate": "",
  "Light-gathering power is proportional to the area of the aperture (πr²). Doubling the aperture diameter quadruples the light-gathering power, allowing detection of much fainter objects.": "",
  "What is 'atmospheric distortion' (also called 'seeing')?": "",
  "The absorption of light by interstellar dust": "",
  "The bending of light by a black hole": "",
  "The reflection of light off the Moon's surface": "",
  "The blurring of images caused by turbulence in Earth's atmosphere": "",
  "Atmospheric distortion (seeing) makes stars appear to twinkle and blurs telescope images. It is caused by pockets of air at different temperatures refracting light. Space telescopes and adaptive optics overcome this problem.": "",
  "What is 'spectroscopy'?": "",
  "The technique of measuring the weight of stars": "",
  "The technique of taking photographs of space": "",
  "The technique of splitting light into its component wavelengths to analyze composition and motion": "",
  "The technique of counting stars in a galaxy": "",
  "Spectroscopy splits light into a spectrum, revealing absorption and emission lines that identify chemical elements, temperature, density, and radial velocity (via Doppler shift) of celestial objects.": "",
  "What is a 'space probe'?": "",
  "An unmanned spacecraft sent to explore celestial bodies and collect data": "",
  "A type of antenna used for radio telescopes": "",
  "A handheld tool used by astronauts on spacewalks": "",
  "A manned spacecraft that orbits Earth": "",
  "Space probes are robotic vehicles sent to other planets, moons, asteroids, or beyond the solar system. Examples include Voyager, New Horizons (Pluto flyby), and the Mars rovers.": "",
  "What does 'resolution' mean for a telescope?": "",
  "The ability to distinguish fine details or separate closely spaced objects": "",
  "The size of the telescope building": "",
  "The number of colors a telescope can see": "",
  "The total weight of the telescope": "",
  "Resolution (angular resolution) is how well a telescope can distinguish two closely spaced objects. Higher resolution means sharper, more detailed images. It improves with larger aperture and shorter wavelength.": "",
  "What is the 'Lagrange point' where JWST orbits?": "",
  "A point in space where the gravitational pull of two bodies balances, allowing stable orbits": "",
  "The edge of the observable universe": "",
  "The center of the Milky Way galaxy": "",
  "The closest point of a planet's orbit to the Sun": "",
  "JWST orbits at the Sun-Earth L2 Lagrange point, about 1.5 million km from Earth. At L2, the combined gravity of the Sun and Earth allows JWST to orbit the Sun in sync with Earth while staying in Earth's shadow.": "",
  "An astronomy class compares images of the same nebula taken by Hubble (visible light) and Spitzer (infrared). The infrared image reveals stars hidden by dust. Why?": "",
  "The dust only exists in the visible-light image": "",
  "Spitzer is simply a more powerful telescope than Hubble": "",
  "Infrared light can pass through dust clouds that block visible light": "",
  "Infrared cameras use better film than visible-light cameras": "",
  "Dust grains absorb and scatter visible light but allow longer-wavelength infrared light to pass through. This is why infrared telescopes like Spitzer and JWST can reveal objects hidden behind dust clouds.": "",
  "A student notices that stars twinkle when seen from the ground but not from photos taken by Hubble. What explains the difference?": "",
  "Hubble is above the atmosphere, so atmospheric turbulence doesn't blur its images": "",
  "Stars only twinkle at night, and Hubble only observes during the day": "",
  "Hubble uses a special anti-twinkle filter": "",
  "Ground-based telescopes are always broken": "",
  "Twinkling (scintillation) is caused by turbulence in Earth's atmosphere bending starlight. Hubble orbits above the atmosphere at about 540 km altitude, so it sees steady, unblurred starlight.": "",
  "A radio astronomer can observe a distant galaxy on a cloudy night, but an optical astronomer cannot. Why?": "",
  "Radio waves pass through clouds and atmosphere; visible light is blocked by clouds": "",
  "The optical astronomer forgot to open the dome": "",
  "Radio telescopes are more expensive and therefore more powerful": "",
  "Visible light doesn't travel as far as radio waves": "",
  "Radio waves have much longer wavelengths than visible light and pass through clouds, dust, and even some solid objects. This makes radio telescopes uniquely valuable for observing through Earth's atmosphere.": "",
  "NASA plans to build a new space telescope. Engineers debate between a single 10-meter mirror and a segmented mirror of 25 smaller hexagonal pieces forming a 6.5-meter aperture. What is the main advantage of the segmented design?": "",
  "A segmented mirror can be folded for launch and deployed in space, solving rocket size constraints": "",
  "Segmented mirrors are always cheaper than single mirrors": "",
  "A single 10-meter mirror would be too heavy for gravity on Earth": "",
  "Segmented mirrors produce better color images": "",
  "JWST uses a 6.5-meter segmented mirror made of 18 hexagonal gold-coated beryllium segments. It was folded to fit inside the rocket and unfolded after launch — a revolutionary engineering solution that allowed a much larger mirror than any single-piece mirror that could fit in a rocket fairing.": "",
  "A student says: 'We should build all our telescopes in space since they're better.' What is a valid counterargument?": "",
  "Space telescopes cost much more and are much harder to maintain or repair than ground-based ones": "",
  "Ground-based telescopes actually produce better images than space telescopes": "",
  "Space telescopes can only observe one object their entire lifetime": "",
  "There is no way to launch a telescope into space": "",
  "While space telescopes avoid atmospheric distortion, they cost billions of dollars and are extremely difficult to repair. Ground-based telescopes with adaptive optics can approach space-quality images at a fraction of the cost, making both types essential.": "",
  "The Arecibo radio telescope collapsed in 2020. Scientists said there is no direct replacement for certain observations it could make. What unique feature made Arecibo special?": "",
  "It was the only telescope that could see visible light": "",
  "It was the only telescope powered by solar energy": "",
  "It was the only telescope in the southern hemisphere": "",
  "Its 305-meter dish gave it unmatched sensitivity for radar astronomy and detecting faint signals": "",
  "Arecibo's 305-meter (1,000-foot) dish was one of the largest single-aperture radio telescopes ever built. Its huge collecting area made it ideal for planetary radar, pulsar timing, and searches for extraterrestrial intelligence (SETI).": "",
  "A team discovers a new exoplanet by noticing periodic dips in a star's brightness. What observational technique are they using?": "",
  "Spectroscopy — they split the star's light into colors": "",
  "The transit method — the planet blocks some starlight as it passes in front of the star": "",
  "Astrometry — they measured the star's position shifting": "",
  "Radio astronomy — they detected radio waves from the planet": "",
  "The transit method detects exoplanets by measuring the tiny decrease in a star's brightness when a planet crosses in front of it. NASA's Kepler and TESS missions have discovered thousands of exoplanets this way.": "",
  "JWST orbits at the L2 Lagrange point, 1.5 million km from Earth. If something breaks, astronauts cannot visit to fix it (unlike Hubble). Why was this location chosen despite the risk?": "",
  "L2 was the only location NASA had permission to use": "",
  "L2 has strong gravity that protects the telescope from space debris": "",
  "L2 is the closest point to the nearest star": "",
  "L2 keeps JWST in Earth's shadow, keeping it cold enough for infrared observations while maintaining a stable orbit": "",
  "JWST's infrared detectors must be kept extremely cold (below 50 K). At L2, the sunshield always faces the Sun and Earth, keeping the telescope in permanent shadow. The gravitational balance at L2 means minimal fuel is needed to maintain orbit.": "",
  "Two observatories observe the same supernova remnant — one using an X-ray telescope and one using a visible-light telescope. They see different structures. Why is multi-wavelength astronomy important?": "",
  "The supernova looks different because the observations were taken at different times": "",
  "Different wavelengths reveal different physical processes and structures that no single wavelength shows completely": "",
  "One of the telescopes must be malfunctioning": "",
  "X-ray telescopes always see more detail than visible-light ones": "",
  "X-rays reveal extremely hot gas (millions of degrees) while visible light shows cooler gas and stars. By combining data across the spectrum, astronomers build a complete picture of cosmic objects — something impossible with any single wavelength.": "",
  "A school has $50,000 to buy a telescope. An 8-inch reflector costs $2,000 while an 8-inch refractor costs $8,000. A teacher recommends the reflector. What is the BEST scientific reason?": "",
  "Refractors cannot be used for stargazing": "",
  "Reflecting telescopes avoid chromatic aberration and are more cost-effective at larger apertures": "",
  "Reflecting telescopes are always more accurate than refractors": "",
  "The reflector weighs less because it uses no glass": "",
  "Reflecting telescopes use mirrors that reflect all wavelengths equally (no chromatic aberration), and mirrors are easier and cheaper to manufacture at large sizes than lenses. For the same aperture, reflectors offer better value.": ""
}